        <section id="Gateway of India" class="section">
            <h2>Gateway of India</h2>
            <img src="gateway.jpg" alt="Introduction" class="section-image">
            <p>The Gateway of India is a prominent arch monument located in Mumbai, India, built to commemorate the visit of King George V and Queen Mary in 1911. It stands at the waterfront in the Apollo Bunder area and overlooks the Arabian Sea. The structure, designed in the Indo-Saracenic style, is made of basalt and is 26 meters (85 feet) high. Construction began in 1914 and was completed in 1924. </p>
            <p>The Gateway was originally intended to be a ceremonial entrance for British viceroys and governors, and it later served as the symbolic departure point for the last British troops leaving India in 1948. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Elephanta Caves" class="section">
            <h2>Elephanta Caves</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="About Us" class="section-image">
            <p>The Elephanta Caves, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, are a collection of rock-cut cave temples dedicated to the Hindu god Shiva, located on Elephanta Island (Gharapuri Island) in Mumbai Harbor. These caves are renowned for their exquisite sculptures and intricate carvings, showcasing a unique blend of Hindu and Buddhist art and architecture. </p>
            <p>The sculptures depict various scenes from Hindu mythology, including the marriage of Shiva and Parvati, the cosmic dance of Shiva (Nataraja), and the killing of Andhakasura. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Marine Drive" class="section">
            <h2>Marine Drive</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Services" class="section-image">
            <p>Marine Drive, also known as the "Queen's Necklace", is a 3.6-kilometer (2.2-mile) long promenade in Mumbai, India. It stretches along the Arabian Sea, offering stunning views, especially at night when the streetlights illuminate the curved roadway, resembling a necklace. </p>
            <p>It is located in South Mumbai, connecting Nariman Point to Chowpatty Beach.The promenade is part of the Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose Road.It's a popular spot for walking, jogging, and enjoying the sea breeze. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus" class="section">
            <h2>Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Features" class="section-image">
            <p>Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus (CSMT), formerly Victoria Terminus, is a historic railway station and UNESCO World Heritage Site in Mumbai, India. It's renowned for its Victorian Gothic Revival architecture, blending British and Indian styles. The station is a major transportation hub and a significant landmark, showcasing India's colonial history and its ongoing development. </p>
            <p>CSMT is an outstanding example of Victorian Gothic Revival architecture, with elements like a stone dome, turrets, pointed arches, and an eccentric ground plan. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Colaba Causeway Market" class="section">
            <h2>Colaba Causeway Market</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Colaba Causeway Market">
            <p>Colaba Causeway Market, also known as Fashion Street, is a bustling street market in South Mumbai known for its variety of goods, particularly clothing and accessories. It's a popular destination for both locals and tourists seeking affordable fashion and souvenirs. The market is open from early morning until late at night, with peak hours often being in the evening. </p>
            <p>Diverse Merchandise:You'll find a wide array of items, including clothes, accessories, shoes, electronics, and unique souvenirs.Street Food:The area also features a vibrant street food scene, with numerous stalls offering local delicacies.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="Red Carpet Wax Museum" class="section">
            <h2>Red Carpet Wax Museum</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Contact" class="section-image">
            <p>The Red Carpet Wax Museum in Mumbai, formerly located in R City Mall, Ghatkopar West, is permanently closed. It was known for its larger-than-life wax statues of famous personalities and a snow experience. The museum also featured a Click Art 3D museum. It aimed to provide a red carpet event experience for visitors. </p>
            <p>The museum was located in the R City Mall in Ghatkopar West, and the nearest metro station was Asalpha metro station, which was about 2 km away. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Juhu Beach" class="section">
            <h2>Chowpatty Beach</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Contact" class="section-image">
            <p>Girgaon Chowpatty, also known as Chaupati, is a public beach in Mumbai's Girgaon area, adjacent to Marine Drive. It's a popular spot for tourists and locals, especially known for its Ganesh Visarjan ceremony. The beach is located between the Malabar and Cumbala hills, hence the name Girgaon, derived from Sanskrit words meaning "hill village". </p>
            <p>Location:Girgaon Chowpatty is situated in the Girgaon area of Mumbai, along the coast of the Arabian Sea.Ganesh Visarjan:The beach is a major site for the immersion of Lord Ganesha idols during the Ganesh Chaturthi festival.  </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Hanging Garden" class="section">
            <h2>Hanging Garden</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Contact" class="section-image">
            <p>A "hanging garden" can refer to two main concepts: the legendary Hanging Gardens of Babylon, one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, and more practically, a garden constructed on a vertical surface or elevated platform. The Hanging Gardens of Babylon, if they existed as described, were a marvel of ancient engineering featuring tiered structures watered by sophisticated irrigation. Modern hanging gardens, or roof gardens, are a form of sustainable landscape architecture, often used in urban areas to optimize space and improve air quality. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Snow World Mumbai" class="section">
            <h2>Snow World Mumbai</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Contact" class="section-image">
            <p>Snow World Mumbai is an indoor snow-themed park located in Mumbai, offering a variety of snow-related activities and attractions. It's a place where visitors can experience snow, even in the tropical city of Mumbai. </p>
            <p>Activities: Ice skating, snow sledging, snowboarding, tobogganing, and a snowfall experience are some of the activities available.Winter Wonderland: The park creates a snowy environment with snow-covered landscapes, igloos, ice slides, and other winter-themed attractions. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Shree Siddhivinayak Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Shree Siddhivinayak Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Contact" class="section-image">
            <p>Shree Siddhivinayak Temple is a renowned Hindu temple in Mumbai, dedicated to Lord Ganesha, particularly known for its right-trunk idol. It's a popular pilgrimage site believed to fulfill devotees' wishes, especially on Tuesdays and during Chaturthi. The temple, originally built in 1801, is a six-story structure with a gold-plated dome and smaller domes made of gold and other metals. </p>
            <p>Lord Ganesha Idol: The temple houses a unique idol of Ganesha with his trunk turned to the right, symbolizing power and fulfillment of wishes. </p>
        </section>
